\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}$$ \hbox{Cov}({\bf np})={\bf AXA}^T $$\end{document}

From the diagonal elements of this matrix the expected lower bound of the coefficient of variation (CV) of the reconstructed conductivity in the perturbation can be calculated for any voxel. For the evaluation of Eq. 15 the reconstructed value Δp in voxel i follows from Eq. 13:
17\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}$$ \Delta \varvec{p}_i=\sum\limits_{\varvec{j}\in \varvec{P}} \varvec{M}_{ij} \varvec{p}_j^{\ast} $$\end{document} whereby P is the set of the indices of all voxels inside the true perturbation. This equation clearly shows that the CNR must decrease when the size of the perturbation shrinks. Assuming a small perturbation and an approximately constant PSF inside this region the CNR is approximately inversely proportional to the volume of the perturbation. The detectability limit can then be defined as the one where the CNR equals 1.
